				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Legal Charge for Mortgage Settlement Decreases Profit at Bank of America</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Michael Corkery			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-15T11:33:29+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 15, 2014 7:33 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 15, 2014 7:33 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/15/business/dbpix-bofa1/dbpix-bofa1-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/15/business/dbpix-bofa1/dbpix-bofa1-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/15/business/dbpix-bofa1/dbpix-bofa1-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003175811" width="592" height="417" alt="A Bank of America branch office in San Francisco."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="417"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A Bank of America branch office in San Francisco.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Justin Sullivan/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/15/big-legal-charge-drags-down-bank-of-americas-profit/" data-title="Legal Charge for Mortgage Settlement Decreases Profit at Bank of America" data-description="A $5.3 billion charge stemming from a record mortgage settlement overshadowed decent quarterly results in the bankâs investment banking business. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/70858/000007085814000124/bac-9302014ex991.htm">Bank of America Earnings (sec.gov)</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/06/10/business/dealbook/11bank-timelime.html"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/multimedia/icons/interactive_icon.gif" alt="Interactive" width="9" height="9" border="0"> Timeline: Bank of America and the Financial Crisis</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/08/21/business/dealbook/bofa-documents.html">Documents on Bank of America</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t20h47s" class="update">Updated, 8:47 p.m. | </span><a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BAC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Bank of America Corporation">Bank of America</a> said on Wednesday that its profit fell sharply in the third quarter, weighed down by a large legal charge related to its record mortgage settlement with federal and state authorities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bankâs net income dropped to $168 million, compared with $2.5 billion in the period a year earlier, though the decline was not as bad as Wall Street analysts had expected.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After accounting for dividend payments on preferred shares, the results amounted to a loss of a penny a share. Wall Street had been expecting a loss of 9 cents a share, according to a survey of analysts by <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TRI&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Thomson Reuters Corporation">Thomson Reuters</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bankâs revenue fell about 1 percent, to $21.43 billion, slightly topping analystsâ estimates of $21.36 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In August, Bank of America agreed to a $16.65 billion deal with federal and state authorities to settle civil charges related to its sale of shoddy mortgage securities. The third-quarter results, however, are a reminder that the bank has not yet put the financial crisis behind it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The cost of the settlement â which continued to grow as the bank and prosecutors neared a deal this summer â accounted for the majority of the $5.3 billion charge, obscuring otherwise decent quarterly results in the bankâs investment banking and credit-card businesses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While the Justice Department settlement represents the costliest case Bank of America has faced, the bank said on Wednesday that it still faced other litigation expenses related to the mortgage crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On a volatile day for stocks in general, shares of Bank of America dropped 76 cents, or 4.6 percent, to $15.76.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Putting aside the bankâs legal costs, the third-quarter results reflect the bankâs challenges in increasing revenue during a sluggish economy. Driving much of the profit gains across many of the bankâs businesses was its continued success at cutting expenses. Excluding legal charges, the bankâs overall expenses decreased. Noninterest expenses fell 7 percent from the period a year earlier.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe remain focused on streamlining and simplifying our company and connecting customers and clients with the real economy, an approach that is paying dividends for them and for our shareholders,â Bank of Americaâs chief executive, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/brian_t_moynihan/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Brian T. Moynihan.">Brian T. Moynihan</a>, said in a statement</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bank of America, which is often seen as a bellwether for consumer banking, continued to experience lower charge-offs as it wound down troubled loans on its books while making new loans with higher credit quality.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But growth in the consumer business remains challenging for all big banks and could become increasingly difficult while there are signs of a global economic slowdown and concerns over the Ebola outbreak.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWeâve seen growth grinding forward in a 2 to 4 percent area,â the bankâs chief financial officer, Bruce R. Thompson, said in a call with reporters on Wednesday, adding that there were some issues globally that could dampen that outlook. âWe are cognizant of a variety of external factors, whether they be health concerns or conflicts that are out there.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, one area of consumer growth was in credit cards. The company issued 1.2 million new credit cards in the quarter, a 15 percent increase from the third quarter of 2013.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Tuesday, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &#038; Company">JPMorgan Chase</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=C&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Citigroup Inc">Citigroup</a> reported higher profits, helped by the improving trading environment and lower credit losses. <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=WFC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Wells Fargo &#038; Company">Wells Fargo</a> also said profit increased in the third quarter, even as the mortgage business, that bankâs traditional source of strength, remained sluggish.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bank of America is not the only bank to be dogged by increased legal costs. JPMorganâs third-quarter results were slowed by the $1.1 billion the bank set aside for legal costs, much of it to deal with an investigation into potential manipulation of the foreign exchange market by the biggest global banks.</p>
